# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albanian-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In 1997, Albania experienced a severe political, economic and security crisis after the collapse of large-scale pyramid investment schemes.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The schemes had attracted deposits from a large share of the population and accumulated liabilities estimated at more than US$1 billion, close to half of Albania's gross domestic product at the time.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Their collapse triggered mass protests, especially in Vlorë and other southern towns, and developed into a broader rebellion against President Sali Berisha and the Democratic Party government.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] By March 1997, the government had lost control of large parts of the south; police and army units deserted or disintegrated in many areas, armed civilians and criminal groups seized weapons, and local Salvation Committees and gangs took over public functions in several towns.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Various sources describe the events as a rebellion, anarchy, near civil war, or civil war, although the terminology remains debated.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Prime Minister Aleksandër Meksi resigned on 1 March, while Berisha declared a state of emergency and was re-elected by parliament on 3 March amid the collapse of public order.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Under international mediation, a Government of National Reconciliation led by Socialist politician Bashkim Fino was formed on 9 March and early parliamentary elections were scheduled for June and July.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 28 March, the United Nations Security Council adopted Resolution 1101, authorising an Italian-led multinational protection force to facilitate humanitarian assistance and help create a secure environment for international missions in Albania.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The force, known as Operation Alba, began deploying in April.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The unrest caused approximately 2,000 deaths and thousands of injuries, large-scale destruction of public property, mass emigration and a major security problem from looted weapons.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] According to UNDP estimates cited in studies of Albania's post-1997 disarmament, hundreds of thousands of weapons and large quantities of ammunition, grenades and mines were taken from state depots.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The 1997 elections removed Berisha from power and brought the Socialist Party-led coalition to government; Rexhep Meidani was elected president.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Some weapons looted during the crisis later circulated in the region, including in the build-up to the Kosovo War.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The period has been described as a civil war, on the brink of civil war, or near civil war, and as anarchy, while others argue that it was not.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] After the fall of communist rule in 1991, Albania underwent a rapid transition from a highly centralised economy to political pluralism and market reforms.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The country remained one of the poorest in Europe, with weak financial supervision, limited public trust in institutions, high unemployment and large-scale emigration.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The 1996 Albanian parliamentary election deepened the political crisis.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Human Rights Watch reported physical violence, ballot stuffing and voter-list manipulation in the 1996 elections, while opposition parties refused to recognise the result.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The Democratic Party retained overwhelming parliamentary control, but the disputed vote damaged the legitimacy of state institutions and increased opposition mobilisation.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] When the pyramid schemes began to fail later in 1996 and early 1997, financial losses merged with broader grievances about corruption, state capture, electoral manipulation and repression of dissent.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The immediate cause of the unrest was the collapse of pyramid investment schemes in late 1996 and early 1997.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The schemes had grown in a context of weak banking regulation, limited financial literacy and public tolerance by officials who often treated them as normal investment companies rather than fraudulent liabilities.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The financial collapse quickly became political.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Many depositors believed that the government had tolerated or benefited from the schemes, while opposition groups connected the losses to wider allegations of corruption, authoritarianism and the disputed 1996 elections.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The weakening of police and army discipline, the spread of weapons after military depots were looted, and the rise of local armed groups transformed the protests from a financial crisis into a nationwide breakdown of public order.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 26 May 1996, general elections were held, and the conservative Democratic Party won by a large margin, securing 122 out of 140 seats in Parliament.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] However, the opposition Socialists (PS) accused the government of election fraud and rejected the results.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] They proceeded to leave the ballot-counting process and boycott the parliament.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Five months later, local elections were held on 20 October.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The Democratic Party won again, but the Socialists rejected this result as well.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The collapse of the schemes occurred after several years in which opposition parties, human-rights groups and foreign observers had criticised the concentration of power in the presidency and the ruling Democratic Party.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Human Rights Watch reported that by the end of 1996 the Democratic Party controlled the executive, judiciary, legislature, police, security service and electronic media.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In January and February 1997, as protests spread, police beat and detained hundreds of demonstrators, especially in the south, and the state-run media portrayed the protests as subversive or communist-inspired.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The article therefore treats the unrest as a combination of economic collapse, political confrontation and state breakdown rather than as a single-party or single-cause event.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The first scheme was that of Hajdin Sejdisë, who later fled to Switzerland with several million dollars.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] It was followed by "Sudja," run by shoe factory worker Maksude Kadëna in 1993, and then by the "Populli" foundations, run by an opposition politician, and "Xhaferri." By the end of 1996, the schemes had peaked, with very tempting interest rates; for example, Sudja offered 100% interest.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The schemes were not stopped immediately.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Jarvis argued that the government delayed decisive action, partly because it hoped to distinguish between companies with genuine investments and schemes that were purely fraudulent, and partly because the schemes had become politically and socially embedded.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In January 1997, the schemes finally collapsed.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 22 January, the government froze the assets of the Xhaferri and Populli firms.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] "Gjallica," another firm, was on the verge of bankruptcy, while "Vefa," which had invested in Albanian hotels, the fuel industry, and factories, continued operating as usual.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The first public protests occurred on 16 January in the south of the country.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 19 January, demonstrators protested in the capital, Tirana, over the Sudja scheme.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 24 January, open rebellion effectively began.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Thousands of people in the western town of Lushnjë marched on the city hall to protest the government's support for the schemes, and the protest quickly descended into violence.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Police forces were subsequently routed, and both the city hall and the adjoining cinema were burned down.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] One day later, on 25 January, Tritan Shehu, the leader of the Democratic Party, was sent to Lushnjë to resolve the situation.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Upon arrival, he was captured by protesters and held hostage for several hours at the City Stadium, where he was also assaulted.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Albanian Special Forces intervened to extract Shehu.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] By the morning of 26 January, every government institution in the city had been looted and destroyed, except for the Interior Ministry building, which was protected by the Director of Communications, seven of his engineers, and a guard who refused to abandon his post.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 26–27 January, violence erupted in other southern towns, including the major port city of Vlorë.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 30 January, the Forum for Democracy was formed by opposition parties to try to lead the protests.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Anger was also directed at President Sali Berisha and the government for allowing the schemes to continue.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In Vlorë and other southern towns, these grievances increasingly became demands for the government's resignation.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 4 February, the government began distributing reimbursements for some of the lost money at subsidiaries of the state-owned National Commercial Bank.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Instead of quelling the protests, this move backfired, increasing public suspicion.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] A $550,000 check from the "Gjallica" firm, paid on 7 January to the Socialist Party, accelerated the firm's collapse.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 5 February, Gjallica declared bankruptcy, and on 6 February, violent protests resumed in Vlorë.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 9 February, state police were attacked in Vlorë, and a day later, in the south, a group of 50 Special Forces troops attacked and brutally dispersed protesters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The government's early response to the protests was criticised by human-rights organisations.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Human Rights Watch reported that in January 1997 demonstrations were banned and police beat and detained hundreds of protesters, particularly in the south, where anger was most intense.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The organisation also reported that the secret police, SHIK, harassed opposition politicians, journalists and government critics blamed by state media for inciting the crisis.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] State Department's 1997 human-rights report stated that security forces retained some control in Tirana but lost control and authority in much of the rest of the country.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The crisis also exposed the fragility of Albania's post-communist security institutions.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] As the unrest escalated, police stations and courts were attacked, prisoners escaped, and local commanders often lost the ability to enforce orders.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The collapse of state authority was most visible in the south, but by mid-March armed disorder and looting had spread to northern and central districts as well.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 20 February 1997, approximately 50 students at the University of Vlorë began a hunger strike on campus, demanding the government's resignation and the full return of invested money.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 22 February, the opposition Forum for Democracy declared its support for the strike.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Students from Gjirokastër and Elbasan also came to show their support.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] They were then brought by FRESSH (the Youth Wing of the Socialist Party) activists from Vlorë to Tirana, the capital.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In contrast, the students of the University of Luigj Gurakuqi in Shkodër did not participate in the protest.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 26 February, thousands of people gathered around the university building in Vlorë to defend it against a rumored attack by SHIK (Shërbimi Informativ Kombëtar), the national intelligence service.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On the same day, a group of strikers requested additional medical assistance, raising doubts about the doctors available to them.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 27 February in Shkodër, Mayor Bahri Borici of the United Right declared his support for the hunger strike.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The next day was a decisive moment in Albanian history.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] After strengthening their perimeter around the university building, the rebel forces, without warning, attacked the SHIK building.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In the ensuing fighting between the rebels and government forces, nine people—six officers and three civilians—were killed.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] This incident marked the beginning of a year of violence in southern Albania.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] By early March, the crisis had moved beyond ordinary protest.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The government lost control of Vlorë, Sarandë, Gjirokastër and other southern towns; army and police personnel deserted in large numbers; and armed groups took over roads, ports, police stations and local administrative buildings.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The IMF later described the situation as one in which large parts of the country were no longer under government control, customs posts and tax offices had been burned, and many industries temporarily stopped production.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] This collapse had both political and criminal dimensions.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Local Salvation Committees claimed to represent public order and anti-government demands, while gangs and armed groups used the breakdown to loot banks, seize weapons, settle rivalries and control territory.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The Better Evidence Project describes the conflict as involving both vertical violence against state institutions and horizontal violence among non-state armed groups.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The so-called "opening of the depots" (Albanian: *Hapja e depove*) refers to the opening of the army's weapons depots in the country's northern regions, ordered by President Berisha.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] He justified this decision by citing the need to protect the population from the violence spreading from the south.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] When southern Albanian bases were looted, it was estimated that, on average, every male aged ten and older had at least one firearm and ample ammunition.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] During the rebellion, very large quantities of state weapons were looted from army depots.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The UNDP's 1998 Albanian Human Development Report is commonly cited for the estimate that 656,000 weapons of various types, 1.5 billion rounds of ammunition, 3.5 million hand grenades and one million land mines were taken from state stockpiles.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Later small-arms studies and international weapons-collection programmes treated the 1997 depot looting as one of the central long-term consequences of the crisis.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] At the village of Selitë, near Burrel, a town 90 km north of the capital Tirana, an explosion occurred at an arms depot on 29 April after a group of villagers broke into the facility.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The blast resulted in the deaths of 22 of the 200 village residents, most of whom were from the same family.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The Krrabë Event (Albanian: *Ngjarja e Krrabës*) refers to the theft of gold from the Albanian state treasury on 24 April 1997.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The treasury, hidden in tunnels near Krrabë outside Tirana, contained 340 kg of gold ingots, banknotes, and other items.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The perpetrators, who were later tried and received prison sentences, were: Arian Bishqemi (7 years), Blerim Haka (3 years), Pellumb Dalti (6 years), Enver Hyka (8 years), and Ahmet Hyka (4 years).
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The Robbery of the Northern State Treasury (Albanian: *Grabitja e Thesarit të Veriut*) was the theft of approximately $6 million from the Albanian state treasury in Shkodër in March 1997.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] A group of six people attacked the fortified building with an antitank weapon.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Although the building contained $8 million, the robbers managed to escape with $6 million.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The few police still in the city soon arrived at the scene and took control of the remaining assets.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Later, several witnesses saw the thieves meeting on the outskirts of Shkodër, where they divided the money among themselves.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] After the robbery, police and investigators began their inquiries in Shkodër.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In the spring of 1998, more than a year later, the investigators closed the file and handed it to the police for further investigation.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] International involvement developed in stages.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The OSCE and the European Union first attempted mediation among Albania's political parties, while foreign governments organised evacuations of their citizens as the security situation deteriorated.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 28 March, the United Nations Security Council adopted Resolution 1101, authorising a temporary and limited multinational protection force to facilitate humanitarian assistance and help create a secure environment for international organisations operating in Albania.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The resolution welcomed Italy's offer to lead and command the force and authorised participating states to act in a neutral and impartial way under Chapter VII of the UN Charter.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] On 15 April, Operation Alba began deploying.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Approximately 7,000 soldiers from the Italian-led multinational force were sent to Albania to support humanitarian relief, protect international missions and contribute indirectly to restoring public order.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The force did not replace Albanian authorities or disarm all armed groups, but it helped stabilise Tirana, ports and key routes sufficiently for international assistance and for the early elections to be held under international observation.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] From mid-May, the WEU's Multinational Albanian Police element also assisted efforts to rebuild and retrain the police and support legislative reform.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] These UNSC resolutions provide the basis for establishing and executing the mission (Resolution 1101) and its limited extension (Resolution 1114).
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In March 1997, several nations launched evacuation missions to remove their nationals, embassy personnel, and numerous other civilians by air and sea.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Italy conducted a series of rescue flights and sea evacuations without assigning an overarching name to these actions.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] As part of a peacekeeping mission under UN Security Council Resolution 1101, a multinational protection force of more than 7,000 troops was deployed to Albania in mid-April.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] By mid-August 1997, it had largely restored public order and secured new elections under OSCE supervision.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Under the national reconciliation agreement, early parliamentary elections were held on 29 June 1997, with second-round voting on 6 July in some constituencies.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] ODIHR deployed short-term observers under the Political Contract of 9 May 1997 signed by the main Albanian parties.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] IFES coordinated 100 American observers as part of a larger OSCE-sponsored observer presence that included hundreds of international observers from dozens of countries.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The elections took place alongside a referendum on restoring the monarchy.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The referendum was rejected by 66.7% of the voters, while former Crown Prince Leka claimed that 65.7% had voted in favor.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The parliamentary elections resulted in a major victory for the opposition Socialist Party of Albania, which won 100 of the 151 seats, with turnout reported at 72.6%.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The result ended Berisha's presidency and brought a Socialist-led coalition to power.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The new parliament elected Rexhep Meidani as President of Albania, while the international force and OSCE-supported political process helped stabilise the transition after the collapse of state authority.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Taking advantage of the chaotic situation, criminal groups armed themselves and took control of entire cities.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Most leaders had been imprisoned in Greece but suddenly escaped and returned to Albania.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The most notable case is that of Zani Çaushi, who escaped from the high-security prison in Larissa in February 1997 and, with a group of associates, established the gang of Çole in Vlorë.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In Vlorë, five gangs emerged, but two dominated the city: the Zani and Gaxhai gangs.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The city's activity began at 10:00 a.m., when people gathered in Flag's Square to listen to the Committee of Rescue, and ended at 1:00 p.m.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] After that hour, the streets were deserted, with only gang members remaining active.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The gangs announced through speakers and flyers that others should stay indoors due to impending fighting.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Each night brought attacks involving explosives and gunfire, leaving dozens dead.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In Berat, Altin Dardha's rule was particularly harsh.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] In Lushnjë, Aldo Bare's gang held control, with one of their worst crimes being the beheading of an opponent.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The cities ruled by gangs included Vlorë, Berat, Tepelenë, Memaliaj, Ballsh, Sarandë, Gjirokastër, Lushnjë, Pogradec, Çërrik, and Tropojë.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Salvation Committees (also known as People's Committees or the Committee of Public Salvation [Albanian: *Komiteti i Shpëtimit Publik*]) were organizations formed during the unrest in Albania.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Established in many regions across the country, these committees sought to usurp the functions of the Albanian state.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] They were particularly influential in the south, where, early in the crisis, local Salvation Committees merged to form the National Salvation Committee, which demanded the removal of President Sali Berisha.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] Many of these committees were rooted in local organizations affiliated with the Socialist Party of Albania and saw themselves as protectors of democracy against authoritarian, one-person rule.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p01] The Albanian government, however, perceived them as reminiscent of Communist-era local party organizations and, therefore, as a potential threat of a return to Communist rule.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The following timeline preserves much of the article's earlier chronological detail.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Several entries are based on contemporary Albanian Telegraphic Agency dispatches and other period reporting; some remain disputed or require stronger secondary sourcing.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Casualty estimates vary because much of the violence occurred during the collapse of police, court and hospital records.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Christopher Jarvis wrote that some 2,000 people were killed in the violence that followed the collapse of the pyramid schemes.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Human Rights Watch also reported approximately 2,000 deaths during the popular revolt, the government's response and the ensuing chaos.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Abrahams reported that between March and May 1997 approximately 1,600 people were killed, most of them in shootouts between rival gangs.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] A UNIDIR document claimed that more than 2,000 people were killed in March alone.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Damage from the rebellion was estimated at $200 million, with approximately 3,700 to 5,000 people wounded.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The crisis produced a deep but temporary macroeconomic shock: government revenues collapsed, customs posts and tax offices were burned, the lek depreciated sharply and prices rose in the first half of 1997.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Industrial production and trade were disrupted, while thousands of families were impoverished either by losing savings in the schemes or by the destruction of property during the unrest.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The new Socialist-led government, assisted by the IMF and World Bank, passed legislation in July 1997 to liquidate the pyramid schemes through foreign administrators from international accounting firms.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] According to Jarvis, the administrators gained broad powers to seize and sell assets, fire managers, trace assets abroad and wind down the companies, although the process was delayed by legal challenges, intimidation and the disappearance of liquid assets before the administrators took control.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Lawsuits were filed against leaders of some of the firms, while several officials from the previous government were later prosecuted or tried in absentia.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The political consequences were immediate.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] In the June and July 1997 elections, Berisha and the Democratic Party were voted out of power, the Socialist Party-led coalition won, and Rexhep Meidani became President of Albania.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The last elements of the multinational protection force withdrew in August 1997 after the elections and the initial restoration of order.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The looting of army depots created a long-term security problem for Albania and the wider region.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] Large numbers of firearms remained in civilian hands after 1997, contributing to violent crime, blood feuds and weapons trafficking.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] International weapons-collection programmes in the late 1990s and early 2000s recovered only part of the looted arsenal, and some weapons entered regional conflicts, including the Kosovo War.
[src:albanian-alphabet/1997-albanian-civil-unrest-p02] The crisis also shaped later debates on Albania's state-building, intelligence services, police reform, electoral rules and the role of international intervention in domestic political crises.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] It is similar in shape to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The lowercase version is often written in one of two forms: the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ|.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The latter form is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In English, the name of the letter is the *long A* sound, pronounced /ˈeɪ/.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Its name in most other languages matches the letter's pronunciation in open syllables.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The earliest known ancestor of A is *aleph*—the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet—where it represented a glottal stop [ʔ], as Phoenician only used consonantal letters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter representing a glottal stop—so they adapted the sign to represent the vowel /a/, calling the letter by the similar name *alpha*.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In the earliest Greek inscriptions dating to the 8th century BC following the Greek Dark Ages, the letter rests upon its side.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] However, in the later Greek alphabet it generally resembles the modern capital form—though many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to the Italian Peninsula, and they left the form of alpha unchanged.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] When the Romans adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write Latin, the resulting form used in the Latin script would come to be used to write many other languages, including English.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] During Roman times, there were many variant forms of the letter A.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] First was the monumental or lapidary style, which was used when inscribing on stone or other more permanent media.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] There was also a cursive style used for everyday or utilitarian writing, which was done on more perishable surfaces.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Due to the perishable nature of these surfaces, there are not as many examples of this style as there are of the monumental, but there are still many surviving examples of different types of cursive, such as majuscule cursive, minuscule cursive, and semi-cursive minuscule.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Variants also existed that were intermediate between the monumental and cursive styles.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The known variants include the early semi-uncial (c.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] 4th–8th centuries), and the late semi-uncial (c.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] At the end of the Roman Empire (5th century CE), several variants of the cursive minuscule developed through Western Europe.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Among these were the semi-cursive minuscule of Italy, the Merovingian script in France, the Visigothic script in Spain, and the Insular or Anglo-Irish semi-uncial or Anglo-Saxon majuscule of Great Britain.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] By the ninth century, the Caroline script, which was very similar to the present-day form, was the principal form used in book-making, before the advent of the printing press.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] This form was derived through a combining of prior forms.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] 15th-century Italy saw the formation of the two main variants that are known today.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] These variants, the *Italic* and *Roman* forms, were derived from the Caroline Script version.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The Italic form ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *script a*, is often used in handwriting; it consists of a circle with a vertical stroke on its right.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In the hands of medieval Irish and English writers, this form gradually developed from a 5th-century form resembling the Greek letter tau ⟨τ⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The Roman form ⟨a⟩ is found in most printed material, and consists of a small loop with an arc over it.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Both derive from the majuscule form ⟨A⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In Greek handwriting, it was common to join the left leg and horizontal stroke into a single loop, as demonstrated by the uncial version shown.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Many fonts then made the right leg vertical.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In some of these, the serif that began the right leg stroke developed into an arc, resulting in the printed form, while in others it was dropped, resulting in the modern handwritten form.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Graphic designers refer to the *Italic* and *Roman* forms as *single-decker a* and *double decker a* respectively.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Italic type is commonly used to mark emphasis or more generally to distinguish one part of a text from the rest set in Roman type.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] There are some other cases aside from italic type where *script a* ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *Latin alpha*, is used in contrast with Latin ⟨a⟩, such as in the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In English, ⟨a⟩ is the indefinite article (with the alternative form *an* when followed by a vowel).
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The double ⟨aa⟩ sequence does not occur in native English words, but is found in some words derived from foreign languages such as *Aaron* and *aardvark*.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] However, ⟨a⟩ occurs in many common digraphs, all with their own sound or sounds, particularly ⟨ai⟩, ⟨au⟩, ⟨aw⟩, ⟨ay⟩, ⟨ea⟩ and ⟨oa⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨a⟩ denotes an open unrounded vowel, such as /a/, /ä/, or /ɑ/.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] An exception is Saanich, in which ⟨a⟩—and the glyph ⟨Á⟩—stands for a close-mid front unrounded vowel /e/.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The Latin letters ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ have Unicode encodings U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0061 a LATIN SMALL LETTER A.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] These are the same code points as those used in ASCII and ISO 8859.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] There are also precomposed character encodings for ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ with diacritics, for most of those listed above; the remainder are produced using combining diacritics.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] Variant forms of the letter have unique code points for specialist use: the alphanumeric symbols set in mathematics and science, Latin alpha in linguistics, and halfwidth and fullwidth forms for legacy CJK font compatibility.
[src:albanian-alphabet/a] The Cyrillic and Greek homoglyphs of the Latin ⟨A⟩ have separate encodings U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] An **abecedarium** (/ˌeɪ.bi.siˈdɛər.i.əm/ *AY-bee-see-DAIR-ee-əm*; also known as an **abecedary**, the **ABCs** or simply an **ABC**) is an inscription consisting of the letters of an alphabet, almost always listed in order.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Typically, abecedaria (or abecedaries) are practice exercises.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Runic abecedaria are found both in manuscripts, and rune-row inscriptions, such as the Kylver stone (c.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] They typically begin with ᚠᚢᚦ (**fuþ**), followed by runes that vary based on the writing systems being used, be it Elder Fuþark, Anglo-Frisian Fuþorc, Younger Fuþark or Medieval Fuþork.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Some abecedaria include obsolete letters that are not otherwise attested in inscriptions.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] For example, abecedaria in the Etruscan alphabet from Marsiliana (the Tuscan town) include the letters B, D, and O, which indicate sounds not present in the Etruscan language and are therefore not found in Etruscan inscriptions.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Others, such as those known from Safaitic inscriptions, list the letters of the alphabet in different orders, suggesting that the script was casually rather than formally learned.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Some abecedaria found in the Athenian Agora appear to be deliberately incomplete, consisting of only the first three to six letters of the Greek alphabet, and these may have had a magical or ritual significance.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] A deliberately incomplete abecedarium found at Hymettos in Attica may have been a votive offering.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Near the beginning of the Christian era, the Latin alphabet had already undergone its principal changes, and had become a definite system.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The Greek alphabet was growing closer to the Latin alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Towards the 8th century of Rome, the letters assumed their artistic forms and lost their older, narrower ones.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The three letters added by Emperor Claudius have never been found in use in Christian inscriptions.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The letters fell into disuse after Claudius's death.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The alphabet used for monumental inscriptions was very different from the cursive.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The uncial, occurring very rarely on sculptured monuments, and reserved for writing, did not appear until the 4th century.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The majority of objects bearing the abecedaria are not of Christian origin, with the exception of two vases found at Carthage.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] These objects included tablets used by stone-cutters' apprentices while learning their trade.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Stones have also been found in the catacombs, bearing the symbols A, B, C, etc.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] These are arranged, sometimes, in combinations which have puzzled scholars.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] One such stone, found in the cemetery of St.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] This can be compared with a denarius of L.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Children were made to learn the alphabet in pairs of letters, joining the first letter of the alphabet with the last letter (AX), the second letter with the second to last (BV), and so on.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] A stone found at Rome in 1877, and dating from the 6th or 7th century, seems to have been used in a school, as a model for learning the alphabet, and points to the continuance of old methods of teaching.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] An *Abecedary*, a full alphabet carved in stone or written in book form, was historically found in churches, monasteries and other ecclesiastical buildings.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Abecedaries are generally considered to be medieval teaching aids, particularly for the illiterate.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] The alphabet may have been thought to possess supernatural powers along the lines of the runic alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Each letter would have had a symbolic meaning to the devout.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] An example, the first seven letters or so of which were found in 1967, is from the long demolished Church of St Mary of the Grey Friars in Dumfries, Scotland.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] In this case, the letters are inscribed in the Lombardic script of the 1260s and the complete structure would probably have stood near the high altar .
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] One of the oldest examples is now in use as a gravestone in Kilmalkedar, near Dingle, Ireland.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] It has the appearance of a standing stone and is known as the Alphabet Stone, displaying as it does an alphabet dating from early Christian times.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abecedarium] Abecedarian psalms and hymns exist, these are compositions like Psalm 119 in Hebrew, and the Akathist hymn in Greek, in which distinct stanzas or verses commence with successive letters of the alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] The **Abetare** (*Albanian primer*) is an elementary textbook used to teach reading and writing in the Albanian language.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Due to the political and cultural circumstances created by foreign occupation, the Abetare carried an important role in the development of Albanian education and national consciousness.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Through the process of learning to read and write, generations of young Albanians were introduced to the history, language and cultural heritage of their homeland.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] The earliest known Abetare was compiled by Naum Veqilharxhi and published in 1844 under the title "Fort i shkurtër e i përdorshëm Ëvetar shqip" (*"A Very Short and Practical Albanian Primer"*).
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] It included a programmatic preface that outlined educational and cultural aims associated with the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] The work was republished in 1845 as "Fare i ri Ëvetar shqip për djem nismëtarë", expanding to 50 pages and supplemented with additional reading materials.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] A major contribution to early Albanian primers was made by Kostandin Kristoforidhi, who in 1867 published primers in both the Gheg and Tosk dialects.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] These works were later reprinted and widely used for teaching Albanian during his travels throughout the Albanian-speaking Balkans.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] In the late 19th century, the production of Albanian-language primers intensified alongside the broader national movement.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] During the period of the League of Prizren, the preparation of primers and other educational texts became closely linked to initiatives aimed at promoting Albanian language and schooling.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] In this context, a new primer titled "Alfabetarja e gjuhës shqip" was published in Istanbul, in 1879 by Jani Vreto, Sami Frashëri, Pashko Vasa and Koto Hoxhi.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] This publication represented a significant step in the development of Albanian school textbooks and contributed to the gradual formation of a national educational framework.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Primers of this period typically combined basic language instruction with reading passages, poetry and introductory material on nature and Albanian history, reflecting advances in both content and pedagogical structure.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Throughout the 19th century, primers intended for young learners were published in both major Albanian dialects, often incorporating historical and literary texts.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Authors of this period included Daut Boriçi and Anastas Kullurioti.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] In the years preceding Albania's independence, the number of primers increased.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Luigj Gurakuqi published "Abetari për Msoitore Filltare t’Shqypniis" in Naples, in 1905, followed by "Abetar i vogël shcyp" in Bucharest, in 1906.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Parashqevi Qiriazi published a primer in Manastir for use in primary schools, in 1909.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Additional primers appeared in Paris in 1911, the works of Nikolla Lako and Simon Shuteriqi.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Later contributions came from prominent intellectuals, more notably Aleksandër Xhuvani, Thoma Papapano, Mati Logoreci, Jani Minga, Lazër Lumezi and others.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Following the liberation of the country after World War II, the preparation of primers became more systematized within the framework of the national education system and increasingly grounded in academic and linguistic research.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] The 1947 primer was based on the word method, while the revised 1949 edition by Kolë Xhumari and later reprints, adopted the analytic–synthetic method.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abetare] Specialized primers were also published for special needs groups, including the deaf and visually impaired.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The current **Abkhaz alphabet** is a modified variant of the Cyrillic script used for the Abkhaz language.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Abkhaz was not a written language until the 19th century.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Until then, Abkhazians—especially elites—had been using Greek (until c.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] 9th century), Georgian (9–19th centuries), and partially Turkish (18th century).
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The first Abkhaz alphabet was created in 1862 by Peter von Uslar.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] It had 55 letters and was based on the Cyrillic script.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Another version, having 51 letters, was used in 1892 by Dimitry Gulia and K.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1909, the alphabet was again expanded to 55 letters by Andria Tchotchua to adjust to the extensive consonantal inventory of Abkhaz.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1926, during the *korenizatsiya* policy in the Soviet Union, the Cyrillic alphabet was replaced by a Latin alphabet devised by Nikolay Marr.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] It featured 76 letters and was called the "Abkhaz analytical alphabet".
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1928, this was replaced by another Latin alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] From 1938 to 1954 the Abkhaz language was written in Georgian *Mkhedruli script*.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Since 1954, the Abkhaz language has been written in a new 58-letter (now 64-letter) Cyrillic alphabet (see chart below).
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Of these, 38 are graphically distinct; the rest are digraphs with ⟨ь⟩ and ⟨ә⟩ which indicate palatalization and labialization, respectively.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1996, the most recent reform of the alphabet was implemented: while labialization had hitherto been marked with two additional letters, ә and у (у was used in the digraphs гу, ҕу, ку, қу, ҟу, and ху, which were not considered separate letters), since then only ә was retained in this function.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Unusually, the Cyrillic plosive letters к п т represent ejective consonants; the non-ejectives (pulmonic consonants) are derived from these by means of a descender at the bottom of the letter.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In the case of the affricates, however, the plain letters are pulmonic, and the derived letters ejective.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The modern Abkhaz orthography gives preference to the letters г к п т х ч with descender (ӷ қ ԥ ҭ ҳ ҷ).
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The letters (ҕ ҧ) had previously (before 1996) had a hook, which ҕ still does in Yakut.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In pre-Soviet alphabets the hook was also used in ӄ ꚋ, see above.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The letters ь and ә are used as parts of digraphs, but are listed separately in the alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Besides the digraphs listed in the alphabet, the letter ь occurs in ль /lʲ/, which is used in some loanwords.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Letters or digraphs in brackets are not part of the alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Letters without a modern equivalent represent phonemes only present in the Bzyb dialect, as the literary standard dialect switched from Bzyb to Abzhywa.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] During the government of Enver Hoxha, Albania had a natalist policy, leading women to have abortions performed illegally or inducing them on their own.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] Women found guilty of aborting their pregnancies would either be shamed socially by the Party of Labour of Albania or sent to work in a reeducation program.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] As with many other developing countries, sex-selective abortion is a common practice in the region, with author Marjola Rukaj commenting, "If it's a male, all is well.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] In Albania selective abortion is a widespread practice.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] In 1989, abortion was legalized in the case of rape and incest or if the patient was under the age of 16.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] In 1991 abortion-by-application was introduced, allowing women to terminate their pregnancies for a variety of reasons if a board of medical practitioners agreed it was the best decision.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] The 1995 law nullifies all previous laws.
[src:albanian-alphabet/abortion-in-albania] As of 2019, the abortion rate was 9 abortions per 1000 women aged 15–49 years.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] AKEP recommends that .al domain registrations be performed with one of the AKEP accredited registrars.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] There are also international registrars that resell .al domains.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] Domain names should be between 2 and 63 characters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] Although the Albanian language has a number of special characters, the registry has not enabled the use of IDN characters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] In the past, registrations were not permitted directly at the second level, but a few existing names were "grandfathered"; they were **uniti.al**, **tirana.al**, **soros.al**, **upt.al** and **inima.al**.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] In 2012 registrars started to resell .al domain names widely making them popular outside Albania as domain hacks.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] In November 2014 the registry released two character domain names allowing for free landrush.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] Registrations used to be only beneath the second-levels, i.e., **.com.al**, **.net.al**, **.org.al**, and **.edu.al** labeled appropriately for the type of organisation, but many now exist directly below .al.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] As of November 1, 2019, the Autoriteti i Komunikimeve Elektronike dhe Postare (AKEP) has mandated that all AKEP accredited registrars begin verifying and updating the WHOIS contact information for all new domain registrations and Registrant contact modifications.
[src:albanian-alphabet/al] As of the end of 2022 there were 27,275 registered .al-domains.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The **Albanian alphabet** (Albanian: *abetarja shqipe*) is a variant of the Latin alphabet used to write the Albanian language.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The letters are named simply by their sounds, followed by ë for consonants (e.g. shë).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Listenⓘ to the pronunciation of the 36 letters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The earliest known mention of Albanian writings comes from a French Catholic church document from 1332.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Scholars warn that this could mean Albanians also wrote in the Latin language, not necessarily just Albanian with a Latin script.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The history of the later Albanian alphabet is closely linked with the influence of religion among Albanians.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The writers from the North of Albania used Latin letters under the influence of the Catholic Church, those from the South of Albania under the Greek Orthodox church used Greek letters, while others used Arabic letters under the influence of Islam.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] There were also attempts for an original Albanian alphabet in the period of 1750–1850.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The current alphabet in use among Albanians is one of the two variants approved in the Congress of Manastir held by Albanian intellectuals from 14 to 22 November 1908, in Manastir (Bitola, North Macedonia).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The first certain document in Albanian is the *Formula e pagëzimit* (1462) (baptismal formula), issued by Pal Engjëlli (1417–1470); it was written in Latin characters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] It was a simple phrase that was supposed to be used by the relatives of a dying person if they could not make it to churches during the troubled times of the Ottoman invasion.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The Greek intellectual Anastasios Michael, in his speech to the Berlin Academy (c.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] 1707) mentions an Albanian alphabet produced "recently" by Kosmas from Cyprus, bishop of Dyrrachium.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] It is assumed that this is the alphabet used later for the "Gospel of Elbasan".
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Anastasios calls Kosmas the "Cadmus of Albania".
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In 1857 Kostandin Kristoforidhi, an Albanian scholar and translator, drafted in Istanbul, Ottoman Empire, a *Memorandum for the Albanian language*.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] He then went to Malta, where he stayed until 1860 in a Protestant seminary, finishing the translation of *The New Testament* in the Tosk and Gheg dialects.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] He was helped by Nikolla Serreqi from Shkodër with the Gheg version of the New Testament.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Nikolla Serreqi was also the propulsor for the use of the Latin script for the translation of the New Testament, which had already been used by the early writers of the Albanian literature; Kristoforidhi enthusiastically embraced the idea of a Latin alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In November 1869, a Commission for the Alphabet of the Albanian Language was gathered in Istanbul.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] One of its members was Kostandin Kristoforidhi and the main purpose of the commission was the creation of a unique alphabet for all the Albanians.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In January 1870 the commission ended its work of the standardisation of the alphabet, which was mainly in Latin letters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] A plan on the creation of textbooks and spread of Albanian schools was drafted.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] However this plan was not realized, because the Ottoman government would not finance the expenses for the establishment of such schools.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Although this commission had gathered and delivered an alphabet in 1870, the writers from the North still used the Latin-based alphabet, whereas in southern Albania writers used mostly the Greek letters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In southern Albania, the main activity of Albanian writers consisted in translating Greek Orthodox religious texts, and not in forming any kind of literature which could form a strong tradition for the use of Greek letters.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The turning point was the aftermath of the League of Prizren (1878) events when in 1879 Sami Frashëri and Naim Frashëri formed the Society for the Publication of Albanian Writings.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Sami Frashëri, Koto Hoxhi, Pashko Vasa and Jani Vreto created an alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] This was based on the principle of "one sound one letter" (although the revision of 1908 replaced the letter *ρ* with the *rr* digraph to avoid confusion with *p*).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] This was called the "Istanbul alphabet" (also "Frashëri alphabet").
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In 1905 this alphabet was in widespread use in all Albanian territory, North and South, including Catholic, Muslim and Orthodox areas.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] One year earlier, in 1904 had been published the Albanian dictionary (Albanian: *Fjalori i Gjuhës Shqipe*) of Kostandin Kristoforidhi, after the author's death.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The dictionary had been drafted 25 years before its publication and was written in the Greek alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The so-called *Bashkimi* alphabet was designed by the Society for the Unity of the Albanian Language for being written on a French typewriter and includes no diacritics other than *é* (compared to ten graphemes of the Istanbul alphabet which were either non-Latin or had diacritics).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In 1908, the Congress of Manastir was held by Albanian intellectuals in Bitola, in what is now the Republic of North Macedonia.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The Congress was hosted by the *Bashkimi* ("unity") club, and prominent delegates included Gjergj Fishta, Ndre Mjeda, Mit'hat Frashëri, Sotir Peçi, Shahin Kolonja, and Gjergj D.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] There was much debate and the contending alphabets were *Istanbul*, *Bashkimi* and *Agimi*.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] However, the Congress was unable to make a clear decision and opted for a compromise solution of using both the widely used *Istanbul*, with minor changes, and a modified version of the *Bashkimi* alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Usage of the alphabet of Istanbul declined rapidly and it was essentially extinct over the following decades, due largely to its inconvenience in requiring new custom-made glyphs that Bashkimi did not.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] During 1909 and 1910 there were movements by members of the Young Turks to adopt an Arabic alphabet, as they considered the Latin script to be un-Islamic.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In Korçë and Gjirokastër, demonstrations took place favoring the Latin script, and in Elbasan, Muslim clerics led a demonstration for the Arabic script, telling their congregations that using the Latin script would make them infidels.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In 1911, the Young Turks dropped their opposition to the Latin script; finally, the Latin *Bashkimi* alphabet was adopted, and is still in use today.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The modifications to the Bashkimi alphabet were made to include characters used in the Istanbul and Agimi alphabets.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] *Ç* was chosen over *ch* since *c with cedilla* could be found on every typewriter, given its use in French.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Other changes were more esthetic and as a way to combine the three scripts.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] A second congress at Manastir (Bitola) was held in April 1910, which confirmed the decision taken in the first congress of Manastir.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] After Albanian independence in 1912, there were two alphabets in use.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Following the events of the Balkan wars and World War I, the Bashkimi variant dominated.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The Bashkimi alphabet is at the origin of the official alphabet of the Albanian language in use today.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The digraphs of the Albanian alphabet are the letters Dh, Gj, Ll, Nj, Rr, Sh, Th, Xh, and Zh.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The modern Latin-based Albanian alphabet is the result of long evolution.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Sá škoj nə špiə i þa Linəsə, sə moterəsə. „Ḱyr sá e bukurə âšt kəjo mołə!
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] A primer was published in 1861 in Constantinople by Daut Boriçi, prominent figure of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The last version was published in 1911 by Rexhep Voka, another prominent figure of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In addition, Buzuku's Latin-based alphabet included five Cyrillic letters, three of which continued into the Catholic alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The Franco-Danish geographer Conrad Malte-Brun sparked interest in developing an Albanian alphabet in the 18th century.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] In his Universal Geography published in 1826 Malte-Brun mentions an Albanian "ecclesiastical alphabet, which consists of thirty letters." After him Johann Georg von Hahn, Leopold Geitler, Gjergj Pekmezi and others continued studies on the same topic.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Seven original Albanian scripts have been discovered since.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Before the standardisation of the Albanian alphabet, there were several ways of writing the sounds peculiar to Albanian, namely ⟨c⟩, ⟨ç⟩, ⟨dh⟩, ⟨ë⟩, ⟨gj⟩, ⟨ll⟩, ⟨nj⟩, ⟨q⟩, ⟨rr⟩, ⟨sh⟩, ⟨th⟩, ⟨x⟩, ⟨xh⟩, ⟨y⟩, ⟨z⟩ and ⟨zh⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Also, ⟨j⟩ was written in more than one way.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The earliest Albanian sources were written by people educated in Italy, as a consequence, the value of the letters were similar to those of the Italian alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The present-day **c** was written with a ⟨z⟩, and the present-day **ç** was written as ⟨c⟩ as late as 1895.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Conversely, the present-day **k** was written as ⟨c⟩ until 1868.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] It was first written as ⟨c⟩ in 1879 by Frashëri but also in 1908 by Pekmezi.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] **ç** itself was first used by Frasheri (1879).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The present-day **dh** was originally written with a character similar to the Greek xi (ξ).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] These characters were used as late as 1895.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] **dh** was also written using the Greek letter delta (δ), while Alimi used ⟨đ⟩ and Frasheri used a ⟨d⟩ with a hook on the top stem of the letter.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] This letter was not always differentiated from **e**.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] These two sounds were not usually differentiated in writing.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] They were variously written as ⟨g⟩, ⟨gh⟩ and ⟨ghi⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] **g** was usually written as ⟨g⟩ or (by Liguori 1867) as ⟨gh⟩, while **gj** was written as ⟨gi⟩ (Leake 1814), ⟨ḡ⟩ (Reinhold 1855), ⟨ǵ⟩ (first used by Lepsius 1863), ⟨gy⟩ (Dozon 1878) and a modified ⟨g⟩ (Frasheri).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The *Grammaire albanaise* (1887) first used **gj**, but it was also used by Librandi (1897).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The older versions of the Albanian alphabet differentiated between two "h" sounds, one for [h] one for the Voiceless velar fricative [x].
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The second sound was written as ⟨h⟩, ⟨kh⟩, ⟨ch⟩, and Greek khi ⟨χ⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] This sound was most commonly written as ⟨j⟩, but some authors (Leake 1814, Lepsius 1863, Kristoforidis 1872, Dozon 1878) wrote this as ⟨y⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Three "l" sounds were distinguished in older Albanian alphabets, represented by IPA as /l ɫ ʎ/.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] This sound was most commonly written as ⟨gn⟩ in Italian fashion.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The *Grammaire albanaise* (1887) first used **nj**.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Blanchi first used ⟨rr⟩ to represent this sound.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] However, also used were Greek rho (ρ) (Miklosich 1870), ⟨ṙ⟩ (Kristoforidis 1872), ⟨rh⟩ (Dozon 1878 and *Grammaire albanaise* 1887), ⟨r̄⟩ (Meyer 1888 and 1891), ⟨r̀⟩ (Alimi) and ⟨p⟩ (Frasheri, who used a modified ⟨p⟩ for [p]).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] These two sounds were not consistently differentiated in the earliest versions of the Albanian alphabet.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] When they were differentiated, **s** was represented by ⟨s⟩ or ⟨ss⟩, while **sh** was represented by ⟨sc⟩, ⟨ſc⟩, ⟨s̄⟩ (Reinhold 1855), ⟨ç⟩ (Dozon 1878) and ⟨š⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Frasheri first used ⟨x⟩ to represent this sound.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Formerly, it was written variously as ⟨ds⟩ (Kristoforidis 1872), ⟨dz⟩, ⟨z⟩, and ⟨zh⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] The *Grammaire albanaise* (1887) first used ⟨xh⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Formerly, it was written variously as ⟨gi⟩, ⟨g⟩, ⟨dš⟩ (Kristoforidis 1872), ⟨dž⟩, ⟨x⟩ and ⟨zh⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Formerly it was written as ȣ (Cyrillic uk), italic ⟨*u*⟩ (Leake 1814), ⟨ü⟩, ⟨ṳ⟩, and ⟨ε⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Leake first used ⟨z⟩ to represent this sound in 1814.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Formerly, it was written variously as a backward 3, Greek zeta (ζ) (Reinhold 1855), ⟨x⟩ (Bashkimi) and a symbol similar to ⟨p⟩ (Altsmar).
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] This sound was variously written as an overlined ζ (Reinhold 1855), ⟨sg⟩ (Rada 1866), ⟨ž⟩, ⟨j⟩ (Dozon 1878), underdotted z, ⟨xh⟩ (Bashkimi), ⟨zc⟩.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] It was also written with a backward 3 in combination: 3gh and 3c.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Arvanites in Greece used the altered Greek alphabet to write in Albanian.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Various remedies are used to graphically distinguish Greek Β from Latin B, including ⟨ʼΒ⟩ for the Greek and Cyrillic ⟨Б⟩ for the Latin, though sometimes it's just a matter of the different typefaces used for Latin and Greek being sufficient.
[src:albanian-alphabet/albanian-alphabet] Sample of Albanian language text, written in Cyrillic characters (central column).
